      "body" : "LinkedList only really faster at removal when the <b>node</b> to be removed is already known. If you&#39;re trying to remove an element, the list must be traversed, with each element being compared until the correct one is found. If you&#39;re trying to remove by index, n traversals must be done. These traversals are super expensive, and the worst case for CPU caching: many jumps around memory in unpredictable ways. See: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YQs6IC-vgmo\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">youtube.com/watch?v=YQs6IC-vgmo</a>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 5072434,
        "reputation" : 13429,
        "user_id" : 4070848,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 39,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9d73132d4bff33a994596034d71de9d1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "drmrbrewer",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4070848/drmrbrewer"
      },
      "edited" : false,
